1
00:01:46,999 --> 00:01:50,534
So he wants to cut it off, just like that?

2
00:01:52,129 --> 00:01:57,800
- He doesn't think you can handle it.
- The arrangements have been concluded.

3
00:01:57,885 --> 00:02:02,595
<i>I gave them my word
because he gave me his word.</i>

4
00:02:02,682 --> 00:02:06,976
- So you tell me why.
- Hey, you know why.

5
00:02:08,814 --> 00:02:11,565
You're not strong any more.

6
00:02:12,609 --> 00:02:15,065
You lost control.

7
00:02:16,530 --> 00:02:20,528
Now, you tell him this:
nothing has changed.

8
00:02:20,618 --> 00:02:24,615
We've had a few setbacks.
That's to be expected in any business.

9
00:02:24,705 --> 00:02:28,999
But I am still in charge,
and I am still strong.

10
00:02:29,502 --> 00:02:31,459
Make no mistake.

11
00:02:31,546 --> 00:02:35,294
You tell him he had better keep his word.

12
00:02:35,383 --> 00:02:38,088
Tell him the 25th, as agreed.

13
00:02:39,512 --> 00:02:43,344
I’ll send him a sign, a little demonstration,

14
00:02:44,392 --> 00:02:47,643
to prove that I’m still strong.

15
00:03:28,856 --> 00:03:33,851
- Good afternoon, Mr Douvier.
- Good afternoon, Simone.

16
00:03:37,615 --> 00:03:40,106
- Any calls?
- On your desk.

17
00:03:49,919 --> 00:03:56,040
- What's this ''Dr Herb called''?
- Your yearly checkup. Tuesday at 4.30.

18
00:03:56,134 --> 00:04:01,556
- Is New York gonna call back?
- Mm-hm. Between five and six.

19
00:04:01,640 --> 00:04:05,804
- Everybody else here?
- Yes, in the boardroom.

20
00:04:15,404 --> 00:04:20,612
Well, l don't think
we should keep them waiting any longer.

21
00:04:25,206 --> 00:04:29,584
- Will l see you tonight?
- Of course, Miss Legree.

22
00:04:41,807 --> 00:04:47,182
Gentlemen, we have a problem.
The Gannet transaction is in jeopardy

23
00:04:47,271 --> 00:04:52,728
because New York feels l no longer
have the power to control the situation.

24
00:04:52,819 --> 00:04:55,571
So l have sent word

25
00:04:55,655 --> 00:05:00,364
that l will give them
a demonstration, a sign,

26
00:05:01,411 --> 00:05:04,745
to show that l am still in control.

27
00:05:04,831 --> 00:05:08,912
That France is still a viable territory.

28
00:05:09,002 --> 00:05:12,454
What I want from you are suggestions.

29
00:05:13,507 --> 00:05:17,172
- I have an idea.
- All right.

30
00:05:17,261 --> 00:05:22,386
Would you ask your secretary
to bring in the morning paper?

31
00:05:23,601 --> 00:05:27,184
- Bring in the morning paper, please.
- Right away, sir.

32
00:05:31,776 --> 00:05:36,771
Who's the most important man in France?
Present company excluded, of course.

33
00:05:36,865 --> 00:05:39,617
Thank you, Miss Legree.
The president, I suppose.

34
00:05:39,701 --> 00:05:45,621
No, for our purpose. A man New York
knows better than the president of France.

35
00:05:45,707 --> 00:05:49,836
A man with which our entire
world organisation is familiar,

36
00:05:49,920 --> 00:05:53,254
and would like nothing better
than to see him out of the way.

37
00:05:53,340 --> 00:05:54,669
Who?

38
00:05:58,554 --> 00:06:02,220
Who has given us nothing but trouble
for the past ten years?

39
00:06:02,308 --> 00:06:06,935
Who has survived
16 assassination attempts,

40
00:06:07,021 --> 00:06:09,726
including two by his own boss?

41
00:06:15,781 --> 00:06:17,026
Clouseau.

42
00:06:17,115 --> 00:06:21,196
You want to impress New York?
Eliminate Clouseau.

43
00:06:21,286 --> 00:06:24,371
We'll have every cop in France
down on our necks.

44
00:06:24,456 --> 00:06:26,745
Not if we do it smart.

45
00:06:26,834 --> 00:06:30,784
There is a rumour
that he is really a complete imbecile.

46
00:06:30,880 --> 00:06:34,463
- I’ve heard that.
- Yet he continues to survive.

47
00:06:34,550 --> 00:06:38,548
I have it on good authority
that he is anything but an imbecile.

48
00:06:38,638 --> 00:06:41,343
That he only plays the fool.

49
00:06:42,267 --> 00:06:45,932
In any case, it is too dangerous.

50
00:06:50,859 --> 00:06:53,646
Can you do it smart?

51
00:06:53,737 --> 00:06:55,231
Yes.

52
00:06:56,115 --> 00:06:57,146
Then do it.

53
00:11:53,801 --> 00:11:55,878
<i>( tenor sings on scratchy record)</i>

54
00:12:13,614 --> 00:12:15,488
Balls?

55
00:12:15,574 --> 00:12:19,358
Inspector Clouseau!
My dear Chief Inspector Clouseau!

56
00:12:19,453 --> 00:12:22,822
How we have missed you!
How we have missed you!

57
00:12:22,915 --> 00:12:26,865
Your disguise is ready for the final fitting.
I think you'll be very pleased.

58
00:12:26,961 --> 00:12:30,211
Cunny! Quick, quick!
Inspector Clouseau is here!

59
00:12:30,298 --> 00:12:34,213
- You have some very interesting noses...
- l will model them for you!

60
00:12:34,302 --> 00:12:38,715
Get on with it, get on with it!
l will bring you one right away.

61
00:12:38,807 --> 00:12:41,512
There were some on the left there.

62
00:12:41,602 --> 00:12:43,345
Ah, the final fitting.

63
00:12:43,437 --> 00:12:47,102
I call this one ''Wino and Roses''.

64
00:12:54,448 --> 00:12:55,907
Magnificent.

65
00:12:56,951 --> 00:13:01,163
Even though l say so myself,
this is no small feat.

66
00:13:01,247 --> 00:13:06,455
Now you can work the Left Bank
and Montmartre with anonymity.

67
00:13:06,544 --> 00:13:10,376
Yes, the old anonymity ploy.

68
00:13:16,597 --> 00:13:20,594
That's it! That's it!
You can do it, Inspector!

69
00:13:20,684 --> 00:13:24,764
- Chief Inspector.
- You can walk, Chief Inspector!

70
00:13:24,855 --> 00:13:27,311
You can walk!

71
00:13:27,400 --> 00:13:29,476
Yes! Yes!

72
00:13:29,568 --> 00:13:32,238
You are a genius, Balls!

73
00:13:32,321 --> 00:13:36,153
l can! l can walk!

74
00:13:40,580 --> 00:13:44,329
Thank heavens

75
00:13:44,417 --> 00:13:48,711
For little girls

76
00:13:48,797 --> 00:13:55,001
They keep on getting smaller every day

77
00:13:55,471 --> 00:13:58,341
Thank heavens

78
00:13:58,432 --> 00:14:02,430
For little girls

79
00:14:02,520 --> 00:14:06,683
They grow down in a most pecu...

80
00:14:08,609 --> 00:14:10,068
Yes?

81
00:14:10,153 --> 00:14:12,110
A special delivery.

82
00:14:13,698 --> 00:14:15,774
Thank you.

83
00:14:17,744 --> 00:14:20,579
I’m sorry, I’m a little short.

84
00:14:20,997 --> 00:14:23,453
Forget it.

85
00:14:23,542 --> 00:14:25,369
<i>(car engine starts)</i>

86
00:14:25,460 --> 00:14:27,537
<i>(car speeds off)</i>

87
00:14:32,176 --> 00:14:36,505
Special delivery. A beum.
Were you expecting one?

88
00:14:37,306 --> 00:14:39,098
A beum?!

89
00:14:39,183 --> 00:14:41,223
Aaaaagh!

90
00:14:50,320 --> 00:14:51,980
<i>(phone)</i>

91
00:14:57,369 --> 00:14:58,911
Yes?

92
00:15:00,998 --> 00:15:02,871
What?!

93
00:15:07,922 --> 00:15:10,591
- Right.
- What's the matter?

94
00:15:12,051 --> 00:15:16,096
The bomb destroyed half the block,
and Clouseau survived.

95
00:15:16,639 --> 00:15:20,008
I am certain, sir,
that the beum was intended for me.

96
00:15:20,101 --> 00:15:22,177
- Beum?
- What?

97
00:15:22,270 --> 00:15:25,057
- You said ''beum''.
- Yes, yes.

98
00:15:25,148 --> 00:15:31,352
Fortunately Professor Balls took refuge
behind a shipment of inflatable goitres

99
00:15:31,446 --> 00:15:33,486
which cushioned the explosion.

100
00:15:33,573 --> 00:15:38,699
- Inflatable goitres?
- Yes. His Valentine's Day collection.

101
00:15:38,787 --> 00:15:40,447
<i>(coughs)</i>

102
00:15:40,539 --> 00:15:43,624
- It's amazing that you survived.
- Yes, sir.

103
00:15:43,709 --> 00:15:49,249
I must apprehend this mad beumer
before he does any more of the damage.

104
00:15:49,340 --> 00:15:51,582
- Or she.
- Or she?

105
00:15:51,676 --> 00:15:53,965
A man dressed as a woman.

106
00:15:58,474 --> 00:16:01,345
Four armed robberies in three weeks.

107
00:16:01,436 --> 00:16:04,805
Two victims were assaulted,
and grappled with the robber.

108
00:16:04,898 --> 00:16:10,023
Both victims said the robber
was much too strong to be a woman.

109
00:16:10,112 --> 00:16:13,860
Three years ago, we sent to prison
a man named Claude Russo.

110
00:16:13,949 --> 00:16:17,817
Russo committed robberies
disguised as a woman.

111
00:16:17,953 --> 00:16:24,288
Well, sir, l must be off
to apprehend this... this mad beumer now.

112
00:16:25,336 --> 00:16:28,456
Remember, it just could be Russo.

113
00:16:28,548 --> 00:16:31,465
Yes. It just could be Russo, yes.

114
00:16:31,551 --> 00:16:34,754
- Yes, l just said that.
- Yes, I know that. Yes, sir.

115
00:16:34,846 --> 00:16:39,638
Well, sir, until we meet again,
and the case is solved.

116
00:16:42,270 --> 00:16:44,347
<i>Au revoir, Hercule.</i>

117
00:16:45,732 --> 00:16:47,891
Fire!

118
00:16:49,987 --> 00:16:52,063
<i>(alarm bell)</i>

119
00:17:04,085 --> 00:17:08,831
You may not have seen these gentlemen
before, but they have worked for you.

120
00:17:09,382 --> 00:17:13,297
And needless to say,
they are specialists, the best in France.

121
00:17:13,720 --> 00:17:16,128
And you expect them
to take care of Clouseau?

122
00:17:16,223 --> 00:17:20,007
Oh, no. They've been contracted
to eliminate Mr Chong.

123
00:17:20,102 --> 00:17:21,845
Who the hell is Mr Chong?

124
00:17:23,689 --> 00:17:25,765
Mr Chong?

125
00:17:28,944 --> 00:17:32,278
Mr Chong was recommended
by Hong Kong.

126
00:17:39,414 --> 00:17:42,450
Gentlemen, fulfil your contract.

127
00:17:43,168 --> 00:17:44,247
<i>(click)</i>

128
00:19:16,307 --> 00:19:17,884
<i>(sneezes)</i>

129
00:19:18,809 --> 00:19:22,143
Why don't you get out of those wet
clothes? You could catch pneumonia.

130
00:19:22,230 --> 00:19:25,681
Yes, I know that.
I will do as soon as I get home,

131
00:19:25,775 --> 00:19:28,729
provided that idiot Cato
does not attack me first.

132
00:19:28,820 --> 00:19:33,233
- Why don't you just tell him not to?
- Believe me, it's not that easy.

133
00:19:33,325 --> 00:19:37,453
l have given him instructions to attack me
wherever and whenever possible,

134
00:19:37,537 --> 00:19:42,283
and it has now become a matter of pride
with him to try to outsmart me.

135
00:19:42,376 --> 00:19:46,208
l guarantee that at this very minute,
his fiendish little yellow brain

136
00:19:46,297 --> 00:19:49,251
is plotting some new ambush.

137
00:19:50,217 --> 00:19:51,628
<i>(sneezes)</i>

138
00:19:51,719 --> 00:19:55,931
- Gesundheit.
- Yes, I know that, I know that.

139
00:20:53,617 --> 00:20:55,693
Cato?

140
00:21:00,166 --> 00:21:02,242
Cato?!

141
00:21:05,838 --> 00:21:07,914
Cato?!

142
00:21:12,428 --> 00:21:14,717
<i>(plays discordant notes)</i>

143
00:21:18,643 --> 00:21:22,855
Pay attention!
This is your employer speaking!

144
00:21:22,939 --> 00:21:27,234
I am cancelling
the attack orders for tonight!

145
00:21:27,319 --> 00:21:29,526
You understand?

146
00:21:29,613 --> 00:21:34,571
I know that I told you to show no mercy,

147
00:21:34,660 --> 00:21:39,239
and to attack, and to pay
no attention to what I say!

148
00:21:41,209 --> 00:21:43,700
But tonight...

149
00:21:43,795 --> 00:21:45,040
<i>(karate yell)</i>

150
00:21:47,131 --> 00:21:49,420
But tonight,

151
00:21:49,509 --> 00:21:53,341
I am ordering you to pay attention!

152
00:21:57,059 --> 00:22:00,013
You will not attack, Cato!

153
00:22:05,609 --> 00:22:07,685
<i>(blows bugle)</i>

154
00:22:08,487 --> 00:22:10,361
Shut up that row!

155
00:22:10,698 --> 00:22:13,615
I am trying to save my life, madam!

156
00:22:21,209 --> 00:22:26,416
Obviously the little yellow swine
is not paying attention.

157
00:22:36,225 --> 00:22:38,301
<i>(feeble karate yell)</i>

158
00:23:06,715 --> 00:23:08,174
Aaagh-ha!

159
00:23:55,641 --> 00:23:57,717
<i>(sawing)</i>

160
00:24:05,068 --> 00:24:07,144
<i>(imitates sawing)</i>

161
00:24:21,043 --> 00:24:24,459
It’s a very substantial building.
We're doing a great deal to it.

162
00:24:24,546 --> 00:24:28,165
I’m sure you'll find it
very peaceful, and quite delightful.

163
00:24:28,259 --> 00:24:30,335
<i>(Cato yells)</i>

164
00:24:44,067 --> 00:24:46,143
A-ha! Ha-ha!

165
00:24:50,115 --> 00:24:52,191
<i>(cone)</i>

166
00:24:55,662 --> 00:24:57,157
Swine!

167
00:24:58,624 --> 00:25:00,913
Chief Inspector Clouseau's residence.

168
00:25:01,001 --> 00:25:04,121
<i>- (Douvier) Clouseau?
- One moment, please.</i>

169
00:25:04,213 --> 00:25:06,087
For you.

170
00:25:16,684 --> 00:25:18,511
<i>(woman shrieks)</i>

171
00:25:19,562 --> 00:25:22,136
What on earth is going on?

172
00:25:22,232 --> 00:25:24,937
Excuse me, madame and messieurs.

173
00:25:25,026 --> 00:25:28,811
- I beg your pardon. I am so sorry.
- It’s still for you, Inspector.

174
00:25:28,906 --> 00:25:30,566
<i>Chief Inspector.</i>

175
00:25:30,657 --> 00:25:34,073
Pardon me, I am needed on the telephone.

176
00:25:39,375 --> 00:25:45,496
Hello? This is Chief Inspector Clouseau
speaking on the phone.

177
00:25:45,590 --> 00:25:48,128
<i>Now listen to me carefully, Clouseau.</i>

178
00:25:48,217 --> 00:25:52,595
<i>lf you wanna catch the French
Connection meet me tonight at 11 o'clock,</i>

179
00:25:52,680 --> 00:25:56,050
in the Bois de Boulogne,
near the Grande Cascade.

180
00:25:56,559 --> 00:25:58,848
<i>- And come alone.
- (click)</i>

181
00:26:07,738 --> 00:26:11,570
That's so obvious.
He's bound to think it's a trap.

182
00:26:11,659 --> 00:26:16,487
Yes, or it's so obvious that
he's bound to think it can't be a trap.

183
00:26:16,914 --> 00:26:19,203
It’s so obvious, it's bound to be a trap.

184
00:26:19,292 --> 00:26:22,458
That is why you will never be
a great detective, Cato.

185
00:26:22,545 --> 00:26:25,795
It’s so obvious,
it could not possibly be a trap.

186
00:26:25,882 --> 00:26:30,461
Now, Cato, warm up the Silver Hornet.

187
00:26:54,912 --> 00:27:00,499
Cato, l very much suspect that
the Hornet is overdue for a service.

188
00:27:00,585 --> 00:27:04,749
So if you don't mind,
I’ll use your car tonight.

189
00:27:12,431 --> 00:27:14,507
<i>(sounds horn)</i>

190
00:27:23,984 --> 00:27:27,484
He's driving a white Peugeot.
Licence number is...

191
00:27:47,926 --> 00:27:51,176
By any chance,
are you going to Fontainebleau?

192
00:27:51,263 --> 00:27:53,754
- Well, l...
- Wonderful!

193
00:27:56,477 --> 00:28:00,427
How lucky can a girl get?
You're an absolute darling.

194
00:28:03,776 --> 00:28:06,730
- It’s green.
- It is?

195
00:28:06,821 --> 00:28:08,730
The traffic light.

196
00:28:08,823 --> 00:28:10,021
Oh!

197
00:28:18,250 --> 00:28:25,047
Generally speaking, it's dangerous for a
beautiful girl like you to hitchhike at night.

198
00:28:25,132 --> 00:28:31,301
That's because, generally speaking,
beautiful girls like me don't carry guns.

199
00:28:31,388 --> 00:28:33,465
Yes, yes.

200
00:28:38,813 --> 00:28:42,858
Are you saying that you carry a gun?

201
00:28:42,942 --> 00:28:47,937
Mm-hm. I’ve got it in here somewhere.
It’s not very big.

202
00:28:48,031 --> 00:28:53,026
- Watch it. It might go off.
- Only if you don't do exactly what I say.

203
00:28:54,496 --> 00:28:55,955
Listen, Miss, uh...

204
00:28:56,039 --> 00:28:58,281
- Russo.
- Russo?

205
00:28:58,375 --> 00:29:01,791
<i>(male voice) But you can call me Claude.</i>

206
00:29:04,298 --> 00:29:07,418
- ''Claude''?
- Pull off the road.

207
00:29:07,510 --> 00:29:11,009
The old ''pull off the road'' ploy, eh?

208
00:29:11,097 --> 00:29:16,969
Yes. Then we will see how you do with
the old ''take off all your clothes'' ploy.

209
00:29:46,008 --> 00:29:49,543
lf you don't want to freeze to death,
you'd better put on the dress.

210
00:29:49,637 --> 00:29:51,926
- Never!
- Suit yourself.

211
00:29:52,015 --> 00:29:56,641
But the dress is an original Dior,
and you've got sensational legs.

212
00:29:56,728 --> 00:29:58,187
<i>(blows kiss)</i>

213
00:30:04,736 --> 00:30:07,062
<i>(whistles)</i>

214
00:30:31,765 --> 00:30:33,175
<i>(phone)</i>

215
00:30:33,266 --> 00:30:35,342
<i>(man) Merde!</i>

216
00:30:37,771 --> 00:30:39,230
Yes?

217
00:30:41,149 --> 00:30:44,150
Oh... Good. Thank you.

218
00:30:44,236 --> 00:30:47,819
- Why don't you take it off the hook?
- Won't be necessary, my dear.

219
00:30:47,906 --> 00:30:51,987
The great Inspector Clouseau
will not be bothering us any more.

220
00:30:59,252 --> 00:31:01,043
Hello, boys!

221
00:31:01,129 --> 00:31:04,332
Oh! Am I glad to see you!

222
00:31:04,924 --> 00:31:07,961
And we are certainly glad to see you.

223
00:31:08,053 --> 00:31:11,422
Hey, hey, hey!
Wait a moment! Wait a moment!

224
00:31:11,514 --> 00:31:14,219
I am Chief Inspector Clouseau
of the Sûreté!

225
00:31:14,309 --> 00:31:16,385
- And I am Officer Bardot.
- ''Bardot''?

226
00:31:16,478 --> 00:31:18,637
But you can call me Brigitte.

227
00:31:18,730 --> 00:31:22,230
Brigitte! You are making
an understandable mistake.

228
00:31:22,317 --> 00:31:25,687
Don't let my legs fool you.
I’m really a man.

229
00:31:25,779 --> 00:31:27,856
<i>(solemn drum roll)</i>

230
00:31:28,991 --> 00:31:33,949
<i>(man) The palace flag
is lowered to half-mast.</i>

231
00:31:34,038 --> 00:31:38,581
<i>The president has declared
a day of national mourning.</i>

232
00:31:38,668 --> 00:31:44,457
<i>Only a few hours ago, the great detective
stood in this very courtyard,</i>

233
00:31:44,549 --> 00:31:50,469
<i>and was decorated by the president
for outstanding service to his country.</i>

234
00:31:50,555 --> 00:31:53,011
<i>According to the coroner's report,</i>

235
00:31:53,100 --> 00:31:56,551
<i>Chief Inspector Clouseau
was probably dead</i>

236
00:31:56,645 --> 00:32:01,853
<i>before his car hit the telephone pole
and burst into flames.</i>

237
00:32:06,113 --> 00:32:09,317
The president called me
at six o'clock this morning.

238
00:32:09,408 --> 00:32:13,241
A dozen countries have offered
the services of their finest detectives,

239
00:32:13,329 --> 00:32:15,785
but the president made it painfully clear

240
00:32:15,874 --> 00:32:18,828
that this must be solved
by Frenchmen, and quickly.

241
00:32:18,918 --> 00:32:23,213
- Or we can all hand in our resignations.
- l spoke with Dr Laprone at the hospital.

242
00:32:23,298 --> 00:32:27,545
He assures me
that Dreyfus is completely cured.

243
00:32:27,636 --> 00:32:29,178
It’s amazing.

244
00:32:29,263 --> 00:32:34,174
I’ve seen some lunatics in my time, but
they were all pikers compared to Dreyfus.

245
00:32:34,268 --> 00:32:37,637
- He was like a wild animal!
- Didn't he actually bite you?

246
00:32:37,730 --> 00:32:41,016
Oh, yes. On the leg.

247
00:32:41,108 --> 00:32:43,600
l had to take rabies shots, just in case.

248
00:32:43,694 --> 00:32:46,268
The doctor swears
his recovery is complete.

249
00:32:46,364 --> 00:32:51,240
He said that in the last 12 hours,
Dreyfus has literally become a new man.

250
00:32:51,327 --> 00:32:53,404
<i>Thank God for that, because we need him.</i>

251
00:32:53,496 --> 00:32:57,328
<i>lf anyone knows about Clouseau
and who might have murdered him,</i>

252
00:32:57,417 --> 00:33:00,667
<i>that man is former
Chief Inspector Charles Dreyfus.</i>

253
00:33:01,546 --> 00:33:03,872
Isn't it fantastic, Doctor?

254
00:33:03,966 --> 00:33:08,592
Reinstated at my former rank,
with no loss of pay or social benefits.

255
00:33:08,679 --> 00:33:12,214
Yes. It could actually be called
a psychic rebirth.

256
00:33:12,308 --> 00:33:15,225
I’m in your debt.
l shall be eternally grateful.

257
00:33:15,311 --> 00:33:17,932
l only helped. l led the way.

258
00:33:18,022 --> 00:33:21,522
But in the final analysis,
it was your victory, Charles.

259
00:33:21,609 --> 00:33:23,732
<i>Our victory, Paul. (laughs)</i>

260
00:33:23,820 --> 00:33:26,192
But only at the expense of another.

261
00:33:26,281 --> 00:33:29,033
Huh? Oh, Clouseau, you mean.

262
00:33:29,117 --> 00:33:33,578
It could be said that he died
so that you might live.

263
00:33:33,663 --> 00:33:37,448
- l wish l could feel sorry.
- You feel no guilt?

264
00:33:37,542 --> 00:33:39,369
None.

265
00:33:39,461 --> 00:33:42,498
To be honest,
when l first heard he was dead,

266
00:33:42,589 --> 00:33:46,670
there were a few moments
when l was actually convinced

267
00:33:46,760 --> 00:33:49,797
<i>l was in a state of grace. (laughs)</i>

268
00:33:49,889 --> 00:33:54,017
- Is that wrong?
- It isn't a matter of right or wrong.

269
00:33:54,102 --> 00:33:56,141
Look, l hated him.

270
00:33:56,229 --> 00:33:59,680
He literally drove me
out of my mind, as you know.

271
00:33:59,774 --> 00:34:03,523
Isn’t it natural that
l should feel happiness, even joy,

272
00:34:03,611 --> 00:34:08,321
at the thought of him being dead,
out of the way, and gone for ever?

273
00:34:08,408 --> 00:34:13,366
Natural, yes. But there is a danger
that such feelings might promote guilt.

274
00:34:13,455 --> 00:34:16,160
Clouseau would come back
and haunt you.

275
00:34:16,250 --> 00:34:19,037
- I have no guilt.
- Not now.

276
00:34:19,128 --> 00:34:23,956
Not ever. Clouseau is gone,
and I am free, for ever.

277
00:34:24,050 --> 00:34:27,834
- Now, have a cigar.
- Thank you, Charles.

278
00:34:27,929 --> 00:34:30,384
I’ve made the arrangements
for your release.

279
00:34:30,473 --> 00:34:33,509
The Sûreté is sending a car
for you to be picked up at 5.30.

280
00:34:33,601 --> 00:34:36,271
Remember,
you're on probation for 12 months.

281
00:34:36,354 --> 00:34:40,138
lf you have any problems,
call on me immediately.

282
00:34:40,233 --> 00:34:41,941
Thank you, Paul.

283
00:34:48,033 --> 00:34:50,785
Officer, you are making
a most serious mistake.

284
00:34:50,869 --> 00:34:53,906
Release me immediately,
or l will personally see to it

285
00:34:53,998 --> 00:34:57,581
you are transferred to Martinique,
and spend the rest of your career

286
00:34:57,668 --> 00:35:00,622
writing traffic citations
and checking parking meters.

287
00:35:00,713 --> 00:35:04,627
The man who was killed in that car,
my car - uh, Cato's car - was not me.

288
00:35:04,717 --> 00:35:07,339
He was wearing my clothes.
These are his clothes.

289
00:35:07,428 --> 00:35:09,801
I am Chief Inspector Jacques Clouseau.

290
00:35:09,889 --> 00:35:11,847
Miss or Mrs?

291
00:35:11,933 --> 00:35:15,468
You fool! The president himself,
when he decorated me, said:

292
00:35:15,562 --> 00:35:18,433
''Clouseau, you are a man of courage.''

293
00:35:18,523 --> 00:35:21,311
He called me
the greatest detective in all of France!

294
00:35:21,401 --> 00:35:24,402
You charlatan! Impostor!

295
00:35:24,488 --> 00:35:27,240
All right. Calm down, Mr Poirot.

296
00:35:27,324 --> 00:35:29,696
- Poirot?
- Yes!

297
00:35:29,785 --> 00:35:33,534
Yes, but you can call me Hercule.

298
00:35:33,998 --> 00:35:36,999
<i>And l am the greatest detective
in all of France,</i>

299
00:35:37,084 --> 00:35:39,955
the greatest in all the world.

300
00:35:40,046 --> 00:35:41,920
<i>(blows raspberry)</i>

301
00:35:45,385 --> 00:35:47,461
That man is obviously crazy.

302
00:35:47,554 --> 00:35:50,389
Uh-uh. We do not use
that word round here.

303
00:35:50,473 --> 00:35:52,550
Oh? What do you
normally use round here?

304
00:35:52,642 --> 00:35:56,391
- Now, now.
- He is very ''now, now'', l can tell you that.

305
00:35:56,480 --> 00:35:58,437
Court order.

306
00:35:58,524 --> 00:36:03,186
l shall need your signature
on the transfer document.

307
00:36:06,532 --> 00:36:13,069
90 days' comprehensive - thank you -
psychiatric examination.

308
00:36:14,457 --> 00:36:16,117
Hey!

309
00:36:52,830 --> 00:36:54,657
Peekaboo?

310
00:36:56,292 --> 00:36:59,543
Your car's at the entrance, Inspector.

311
00:37:07,179 --> 00:37:10,299
Goodbye, Chief Inspector Dreyfus.

312
00:37:20,443 --> 00:37:25,864
<i>- Good evening, Chief Inspector Dreyfus.
- (gruffly) Good evening, François.</i>

313
00:37:29,869 --> 00:37:33,155
It’s good to have you back on the job,
Chief Inspector.

314
00:37:33,248 --> 00:37:37,080
Is it true that you will take charge
of the Clouseau investigation?

315
00:37:37,169 --> 00:37:40,039
- Yes, yes.
- You must feel torn.

316
00:37:40,130 --> 00:37:45,255
On the one hand, it is your duty to send
the guilty parties to the guillotine.

317
00:37:45,344 --> 00:37:48,428
<i>On the other hand... (laughs)</i>

318
00:37:48,514 --> 00:37:52,428
I am sure you'd rather
congratulate them, eh?

319
00:37:52,518 --> 00:37:55,139
Can you imagine?
A state funeral for that idiot?

320
00:37:55,229 --> 00:37:58,645
The president. Dignitaries from
all over the world will be coming.

321
00:37:58,733 --> 00:38:02,232
Why, there's a rumour
the Pope might even show up.

322
00:38:02,320 --> 00:38:04,396
The Peup?

323
00:38:05,865 --> 00:38:08,072
- ''Peup''?
- What?

324
00:38:08,159 --> 00:38:10,236
You said ''Peup''.

325
00:38:10,328 --> 00:38:13,744
- Do you have a cold?
- Oh, yes. Yes, I have.

326
00:38:13,832 --> 00:38:16,323
I have the cold in the chest, you know.

327
00:38:17,294 --> 00:38:20,461
You sound terrible.
Do you want me to send you a doctor?

328
00:38:20,547 --> 00:38:23,751
No, no. It’s much better than it sounds.

329
00:38:23,842 --> 00:38:27,425
Anyway, I want to go directly
to the Clouseau apartments

330
00:38:27,513 --> 00:38:30,348
to commence the search for the clues.

331
00:38:30,433 --> 00:38:31,595
Yes, sir.

332
00:38:58,754 --> 00:39:02,337
- Is this the Clouseau residence?
- Yes.

333
00:39:08,931 --> 00:39:14,637
This is also the residence
of the Clouseau manservant, Cato Fong?

334
00:39:15,480 --> 00:39:17,354
Yes.

335
00:39:17,440 --> 00:39:23,230
Then be so good as to tell him that l wish
to have speaks with him, would you?

336
00:39:23,321 --> 00:39:28,233
And who should l say
''wish to have speaks'' with Mr Fong?

337
00:39:29,661 --> 00:39:31,987
Tell him it is an old friend.

338
00:39:32,081 --> 00:39:34,572
Mr Fong has many old friends.

339
00:39:34,667 --> 00:39:36,410
Listen, you.

340
00:39:36,502 --> 00:39:42,920
Tell him it is Chief Inspector... Clouseau.

341
00:39:43,009 --> 00:39:47,967
Why didn't you say so in the first place?
Please come in.

342
00:39:57,983 --> 00:39:59,442
Good evening.

343
00:39:59,526 --> 00:40:02,313
- And congratulations.
- What?

344
00:40:02,404 --> 00:40:04,278
You are our first Caucasian,

345
00:40:04,364 --> 00:40:08,232
and that entitles you
to a 10º/% discount until midnight.

346
00:40:08,327 --> 00:40:11,447
- Who are you?
- Mrs Wu. But you can call me Madam.

347
00:40:11,539 --> 00:40:13,412
<i>(doorbell)</i>

348
00:40:14,834 --> 00:40:17,242
- Yes?
- Inspector Clouseau.

349
00:40:17,336 --> 00:40:20,006
Oh! Please come in.

350
00:40:20,089 --> 00:40:22,296
- Madam.
- Welcome.

351
00:40:22,383 --> 00:40:26,631
- Good evening.
- Please, make yourself at home.

352
00:40:27,681 --> 00:40:30,385
That man just called himself
Inspector Clouseau.

353
00:40:30,475 --> 00:40:35,351
It was Mr Fong's idea, but personally,
I think we should have a better password.

354
00:40:35,439 --> 00:40:37,313
Password?!

355
00:40:44,240 --> 00:40:48,024
Madam, l demand to know
exactly what is going on in here.

356
00:40:48,119 --> 00:40:51,488
Well, just about anything
your little heart desires.

357
00:40:51,581 --> 00:40:54,250
But first, why don't you relax?

358
00:40:54,333 --> 00:40:59,708
Give Benson your hat and your coat,
have a drink, get to know the girls.

359
00:40:59,798 --> 00:41:01,956
And then, when you are up to it,

360
00:41:02,050 --> 00:41:07,257
you can choose from a wide variety
of exciting little diversions.

361
00:41:10,058 --> 00:41:13,890
But I see that
you already have a preference.

362
00:41:23,948 --> 00:41:28,160
Allow me to introduce
Tanya, the Lotus Eater.

363
00:41:29,203 --> 00:41:32,074
What else does she do?

364
00:41:37,545 --> 00:41:40,749
l warn you, Tanya the Easter Lotus,

365
00:41:40,841 --> 00:41:44,174
I am opposed to the women's libs.

366
00:41:45,220 --> 00:41:49,384
Man is the master,
and women's place is in the home.

367
00:41:49,475 --> 00:41:51,017
<i>- (whip swishes)
- Ooh! Ow!</i>

368
00:41:51,560 --> 00:41:54,894
And another round-eye bites the dust.

369
00:41:54,980 --> 00:41:57,057
<i>- (whip)
- Aagh! Aaaow!</i>

370
00:42:06,868 --> 00:42:08,944
Cato!

371
00:42:12,958 --> 00:42:15,034
Aaagh! Ooh!

372
00:42:17,129 --> 00:42:21,079
Take your hands off me, you oriental fool!
You are under arrest!

373
00:42:21,174 --> 00:42:24,840
- Anything you say will be taken down...
- Arrest?!

374
00:42:24,928 --> 00:42:28,214
You have the right to remain silent,
but let me tell you this:

375
00:42:28,307 --> 00:42:31,510
I am not your ordinary,
run-of-the-mill transvestite.

376
00:42:31,602 --> 00:42:34,639
- Say no more!
- What was that talk about arresting us?

377
00:42:34,730 --> 00:42:37,648
- He was just kidding, weren't you, boss?
- Boss?

378
00:42:37,733 --> 00:42:39,940
l used to work for him.
He used to be a cop.

379
00:42:40,028 --> 00:42:43,776
- A cop?!
- Tell them you were kidding, boss.

380
00:42:45,158 --> 00:42:47,993
Yes, he is right.

381
00:42:48,078 --> 00:42:50,995
l was just kidding.

382
00:42:51,081 --> 00:42:56,206
Cross my heart and...
hope to meet you again sometime.

383
00:42:56,295 --> 00:42:58,702
And you, Madam.

384
00:42:58,797 --> 00:43:03,091
And you, too. You two
should be ashamed of yourselves.

385
00:43:03,177 --> 00:43:06,427
And you! I want to talk to you, Cato!

386
00:43:06,514 --> 00:43:10,298
- Here. Come in here. Listen now.
- Please, boss!

387
00:43:10,643 --> 00:43:11,923
l thought you were dead!

388
00:43:12,019 --> 00:43:18,473
So, as a tribute to my memory, you
open up this... Chinese nooky factory!

389
00:43:18,985 --> 00:43:23,149
l had to do something to keep busy.
Besides, a first-rate joint like this

390
00:43:23,240 --> 00:43:28,067
can make as much as
three, four hundred thousand a year!

391
00:43:29,121 --> 00:43:31,493
- Is that net?
- No, gross.

392
00:43:31,582 --> 00:43:35,330
But even so, a smart operator
can clear a coupla hundred grand,

393
00:43:35,419 --> 00:43:37,744
and that ain't exactly chicken feed.

394
00:43:37,838 --> 00:43:39,119
No.

395
00:43:39,215 --> 00:43:45,051
No, and ten years on Devil's Island
ain't exactly the chicken's feed either,

396
00:43:45,137 --> 00:43:47,296
my greedy little yellow pimp.

397
00:43:47,390 --> 00:43:48,635
Ow!

398
00:43:48,725 --> 00:43:52,010
<i>I’ll have to close up anyway,
now that you're alive.</i>

399
00:43:52,103 --> 00:43:58,189
Yes. Yes, normally that is
precisely what you would have to do.

400
00:43:58,276 --> 00:44:01,977
But these are not normal times, Cato.

401
00:44:02,072 --> 00:44:04,943
- Someone has just tried to kill me.
- That's normal.

402
00:44:05,033 --> 00:44:09,162
Ah, but this time
that someone thinks he has succeeded.

403
00:44:09,288 --> 00:44:13,499
Except for you and me,
the whole world believes that I am dead.

404
00:44:13,584 --> 00:44:17,534
And in this case, death has its advantages.

405
00:44:20,383 --> 00:44:22,506
No one will know it is me

406
00:44:22,593 --> 00:44:25,049
<i>as I glide... (coughs)</i>

407
00:44:25,138 --> 00:44:28,092
through the underworld like a shadow.

408
00:44:30,101 --> 00:44:34,645
<i>- Good evening, Commissioner.
- Charles! (laughs)</i>

409
00:44:34,731 --> 00:44:36,605
I, uh...

410
00:44:37,734 --> 00:44:38,849
Thank you.

411
00:44:38,944 --> 00:44:44,864
I’m sorry to be late, but as you must have
heard, a lunatic was hiding in my closet.

412
00:44:44,950 --> 00:44:47,157
Yes. Russo.

413
00:44:47,244 --> 00:44:48,988
Russo?

414
00:44:49,079 --> 00:44:50,823
Russo...

415
00:44:50,915 --> 00:44:53,702
- Ah!
- You remember?

416
00:44:53,793 --> 00:44:56,498
Why wouldn't I?
It was only three years ago.

417
00:44:56,587 --> 00:44:59,505
Of course. Claude Russo.

418
00:44:59,590 --> 00:45:03,671
Alias Claudine Russo.
Armed robbery, dressed as a woman.

419
00:45:03,762 --> 00:45:05,553
But he got five years.

420
00:45:05,638 --> 00:45:08,805
He was released on parole
three months ago.

421
00:45:08,892 --> 00:45:11,300
So it could have been Russo.

422
00:45:11,395 --> 00:45:13,636
He's clever.

423
00:45:13,730 --> 00:45:16,648
- Clever enough to fool François?
- Huh!

424
00:45:17,401 --> 00:45:20,188
l like François, but fooling him

425
00:45:20,279 --> 00:45:25,618
no longer constitutes an act of more
than average cleverness, shall we say?

426
00:45:29,372 --> 00:45:32,622
l always thought
he was rather a good policeman.

427
00:45:32,708 --> 00:45:37,454
When he was my assistant, he was a very
good policeman, with a bright future.

428
00:45:37,547 --> 00:45:41,130
- But then he was assigned to Clouseau.
- Oh, now, now, Charles.

429
00:45:41,217 --> 00:45:44,218
- All that's in the past.
- Yes, of course.

430
00:45:45,138 --> 00:45:49,006
Tomorrow morning,
when they plant him six feet deep

431
00:45:49,101 --> 00:45:51,508
<i>and shovel in the dirt... (laughs)</i>

432
00:45:51,603 --> 00:45:54,391
l shall be truly free.

433
00:45:54,481 --> 00:45:58,610
And unless he's figured out
a way to come back from the dead,

434
00:45:58,694 --> 00:46:03,237
nothing anyone does or says about him
will ever make any difference again.

435
00:46:03,324 --> 00:46:07,073
- Shall we do some work?
- That reminds me.

436
00:46:09,163 --> 00:46:13,624
- What is it?
- The chief wants you to give the eulogy.

437
00:46:13,710 --> 00:46:16,035
- The what?
- The tribute.

438
00:46:16,129 --> 00:46:18,834
- Me?!
- You knew him intimately.

439
00:46:18,924 --> 00:46:20,715
l hated him intimately.

440
00:46:20,801 --> 00:46:24,798
But you're the expert who's
going to track down his murderers.

441
00:46:24,888 --> 00:46:28,838
I’m the expert who
would love to kiss his murderers!

442
00:46:28,934 --> 00:46:31,769
<i>The PR people loved the angle.</i>

443
00:46:33,105 --> 00:46:35,394
It’s sacrilege! l won't do it.

444
00:46:35,483 --> 00:46:36,858
Politics.

445
00:46:36,942 --> 00:46:39,350
No. I’m a good Catholic.

446
00:46:39,445 --> 00:46:42,115
- So's the chief's wife.
- I don't care.

447
00:46:42,198 --> 00:46:44,570
What's she got to do with it?

448
00:46:44,659 --> 00:46:46,865
She wrote the speech.

449
00:46:48,037 --> 00:46:49,995
Ladies and gentlemen,

450
00:46:51,166 --> 00:46:53,538
honoured guests,

451
00:46:53,627 --> 00:46:55,370
<i>dear friends. (clears throat)</i>

452
00:46:56,755 --> 00:47:01,832
We are gathered here to say... goodbye

453
00:47:01,927 --> 00:47:04,085
to a, uh...

454
00:47:05,973 --> 00:47:08,345
a great man.

455
00:47:08,434 --> 00:47:10,058
<i>(stifles laugh)</i>

456
00:47:10,811 --> 00:47:12,887
<i>(coughs)</i>

457
00:47:13,481 --> 00:47:17,431
Not only was he a model police officer,

458
00:47:17,527 --> 00:47:19,934
a brilliant detective,

459
00:47:22,031 --> 00:47:26,361
admired and respected
by his fellow officers,

460
00:47:26,911 --> 00:47:31,040
and all those
who were fortunate enough...

461
00:47:32,084 --> 00:47:34,290
enough...

462
00:47:34,378 --> 00:47:36,454
enough to know him.

463
00:47:37,673 --> 00:47:40,246
He was, above all else,

464
00:47:42,094 --> 00:47:44,170
a modest man.

465
00:48:01,072 --> 00:48:04,239
His kind will not pass this way again,

466
00:48:05,702 --> 00:48:08,027
and our loss is surely...

467
00:48:09,915 --> 00:48:11,991
heaven's gain.

468
00:48:23,095 --> 00:48:25,337
Present arms!

469
00:48:26,390 --> 00:48:28,467
Fire!

470
00:48:34,733 --> 00:48:36,809
Fire!

471
00:48:40,572 --> 00:48:42,648
Fire!

472
00:48:43,617 --> 00:48:46,404
- Get rid of that woman.
- We'll talk about it later.

473
00:48:46,495 --> 00:48:49,698
I want your answer now,
or I sue for divorce.

474
00:48:49,790 --> 00:48:53,076
- I’m warning you, Therese.
- What will you do? Have me killed?

475
00:48:53,169 --> 00:48:55,245
<i>(priest prays in Latin)</i>

476
00:49:23,993 --> 00:49:28,322
Gentlemen... you will be relieved to know

477
00:49:28,414 --> 00:49:33,290
that our friend in New York was very
impressed by our little demonstration.

478
00:49:33,377 --> 00:49:35,536
